<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06276235 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06276235 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  JURY; REPORT; SANTA-CRUZ; COUNTY; JUVENILE; SAFETY; ORGANIZATION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Santa Cruz County's beleaguered Child Protective Services, under fire sincethe Ruby Pointer case came to light this summer, has been taken to task onceagain -- this time by the county grand jury.;    The grand jury was asked bythe Santa Cruz County Board of Supervisors to look into the agency afterPointer's three young daughters were found unable to speak and living in afilthy Santa Cruz townhouse.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  GRAND JURY RAPS CHILD PROTECTIVE SERVICES  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Also ran on page 3B of the Morning Final edition.  </MEMO><TEXT>     On Tuesday the grand jury criticized several aspects of CPS, saying theagency had:;    (check) No method to objectively evaluate the potentiallyharmful situations some children face.;    (check) A high turnover of trained,experienced CPS social workers.;    (check) Files often maintained in&quot;haphazard fashion.&quot;;    The jury called for a better way of assessing risksto local youngsters, urged formation of a pool of temporary workers to helpkeep staff levels up, and recommended that the paperwork system be improvedand computerized.;    Grand jurors also called for a court-appointed specialadvocate program for children. The program would offer advocates to speak onbehalf of children who find their way into the court system either as victimsof abuse or in custody battles involving their parents.;    Chairman FredKeeley said supervisors will discuss Tuesday if and how to set up a system ofchild-advocacy volunteers similar to those in Santa Clara and Marin counties.;   County Administrative Officer Susan Mauriello said after reading the grandjury's interim report that she felt there was local support for the program.;   &quot;I think it can be implemented,&quot; she said.;    Christine Patton, SuperiorCourt administrator, said judges recently named two lawyers to act as specialadvocates for youngsters in legal cases. The lawyers &quot;are the onlyprofessionals who stay with the children all the way through the legalprocess,&quot; she said.;    Saying it intends to delve further into CPS services,the grand jury reported that its preliminary investigation was based on morethan the request of the board of supervisors:;    &quot;It is in response tocitizens' complaints about a chronic lack of timely, appropriate and adequateservices to endangered children.&quot;;    Despite the criticisms, the report saysCPS &quot;generally functions as intended.&quot;;    &quot;However, we have specific concernsregarding the response to sexual abuse and neglect cases,&quot; the report said.&quot;Sadly, whenever mistakes are made, the consequences are tragic for thechildren.&quot;;    The grand jury said more than 4,200 children were referred toCPS during the past fiscal year -- with 161 being placed in foster care. That,they said, was up from fewer than 3,000 children in 1986-'87, when 93 went tofoster homes.;    Pointing to those numbers, the grand jury said bettermethods are needed to determine which children are in &quot;potentially harmfulsituations&quot; requiring immediate attention.;    Last year, the grand jury said,the turnover rate for CPS social workers was 50 percent.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  LEE QUARNSTROM, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Santa Cruz/Monterey  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911002  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  477  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, October 2, 199100276235,SJ1  </DATELINE><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>